The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, May 22, 2004 				 Indian Hotels net leaps 159%
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Mumbai, May 21: Indian Hotels Company Ltd has posted a 158.67 per cent jump in consolidated net profit at Rs 72.61 crore for the year ended March 31, 2004 compared with Rs 28.07 crore in the previous fiscal. The board has recommended an 80 per cent dividend for the year 2003-04.																								Total income on consolidated basis rose by 15.79 per cent to Rs 1,047.4 crore against Rs 904.56 crore in the previous fiscal, the company informed the Bombay Stock Exchange here today.																								On a standalone basis, the company posted a 49.82 per cent rise in net profit to Rs 60.65 crore against Rs 40.48 crore, while total income during the year rose by 17.85 per cent to Rs 696.07 crore against Rs 590.64 crore. For the fourth quarter ended March 2004, the company posted a net profit of Rs 36.81 crore compared with Rs 25.64 crore reported in the corresponding previous quarter. 																								Total income during the reporting quarter increased to Rs 222 crore against Rs 175.97 crore in the same period of 2002-03, the company said. The company has planned a capital expenditure of Rs 160 crore in 2004-05 and will start a national call-centre for marketing and reservations on a round-the-clock basis.																								We plan to use part of the $150 million raised in February 2004 for capital expenditure and acquisitions, said Zubin Dubash, executive director.																								On the performance of the company last fiscal, managing director Raymond . Bickson said improved business environment and strategy to reposition hotels and branding helped to report strong revenues and profit growth. We will start a national call-centre with a toll-free number, Bickson said. These plans are in the formative stage. The company is looking at roping in Tata Consultancy Services for this initiative, he added.Balaji Tele net dips																								Balaji Telefilms Ltd has posted a lower net profit at Rs 55.40 crore for the financial year ended March 31, 2004 compared with Rs 57.41 crore reported in the previous financial year.																								The board has recommended a final dividend of Re 1 for the reporting fiscal, the company informed the Bombay Stock Exchange today. 
